Everyone's path to peace.
Over the next three weeks, the Israeli army will engage in an unprecedented exercise: instead of defending the country against external enemies or terrorists, it will be evacuated by force if necessary, 9,000 Israelis from their homes.
The unilateral withdrawal of Israel is the result of a profound political change caused by two somewhat contradictory convictions that have characterized the policies of Prime Minister Ariel Sharon in 2003: first, that the "road map" originally launched by States - States is going nowhere, then, that the status quo is untenable.
For Sharon, there is no doubt that the 9,000 Jewish settlers living among 1.2 million Palestinians in Gaza are no future.
Therefore, the absence of negotiations, a unilateral withdrawal is the only sensible approach to reducing violence and stabilization.
This policy has deeply divided Israel. The settlers, mostly religious, but not all, are felt betrayed by Sharon, "the father of the settlements."
It is now the Israeli left that, although against - heart, realizes that the new pragmatism preached by Sharon might - be the first step in the right direction.
Like de Gaulle in Algeria, Sharon has reshuffled the cards of Israel's policy.
These past weeks have been part of massive demonstrations, some bordering on violence. Number of settlers have declared that they do not obey the evacuation orders.
The army and the police have mobilized almost 50,000 troops to carry out evictions.
This forcible approach is traumatic not only for the settlers, but also for many other Israelis.
The coming days and weeks ahead will only tell us if the evacuation happens peacefully or not.
In the meantime, Sharon has paid dearly for its policy.
Right-wing parties have left the ruling coalition, he has lost his majority in his own Likud Party, and his finance minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, left his government.
Only by inviting the Labor Party Shimon Peres in his office that Sharon has managed to retain its parliamentary majority.
The question obviously arises on the situation after the withdrawal from Gaza.
Initially, this withdrawal left many skeptical governments, but they have come to realize, as they say in Washington, that was the only thing to do.
Among them, as among Palestinians, some hope that after the Gaza withdrawal will be possible to return to the road map and to resume negotiations leading to a final agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
This is a huge mistake.
Even if it is motivated by the best of intentions, the hope of reviving the road map is not realistic.
Future negotiations will address the last borders between Israel and Palestine, the fate of 200,000 Jewish settlers in the West Bank, the status of Jerusalem and the Palestinian refugee problem in 1947-48.
The gulf between the Israeli and Palestinian positions on these issues has not diminished since the failed negotiations at Camp David in 2000, while fear and distrust have only grow.
Attempt to engage in negotiations in such circumstances would not only be an exercise in futility, but may merely strengthen further the distance and suspicion on both sides.
The failure of the Annan plan for Cyprus suggests that good intentions are not enough - and the disagreements in Cyprus were miniscule compared to what divides Israelis and Palestinians.
What - so it can be done?
The only rational approach is likely to acknowledge that unilateral steps on each side can further promote the cause of the decline in violence and the final reconciliation.
On the Israeli side, further withdrawals of dozens of small isolated West Bank settlements, causing the evacuation of 20,000 to 30,000 settlers, may be politically feasible and would provide the Palestinians a contiguous territory in the West Bank.
On the Palestinian side, consolidation of control by the Palestinian Authority a dozen security services and militias would be an important step forward.
The Palestinian leader, Abu Mazen, recognizes this, but the question is whether it is capable.
The Palestinian Authority could also embark on the difficult road of telling the refugees that, contrary to the assertions of 50 years of Palestinian propaganda, they do not return to Israel, but will have to settle in the West Bank and Gaza the areas that will be part of the final Palestinian state.
In an ideal world, conflicts end by dint of agreements and treaties.
But in real life, as illustrated in Cyprus, Bosnia and Kosovo, stabilization and the slow decline of violence can sometimes achieve the same end, even without formal agreement.
Lack of plausible alternative, one can only hope that this will be the case for Israelis and Palestinians.
