To avoid a lost generation.
Everywhere, young unemployed drifting are a concern.
They are especially a problem in developing countries where a demographic explosion of increasingly strong, the equivalent of the baby boom in the West at the end of the Second World War.
But the aftermath of the war in most developed countries has been an unprecedented era of prosperity for the baby boomers now approaching retirement.
The future it will be as promising for the billion-plus young people aged 12 to 24 years in developing countries?
These countries should urgently combine the investment and the necessary policy measures to encourage young people to form, find work, stay healthy, have a family and practice their citizenship.
The payoff is huge if they get it right: accelerated development through the provision of a young population and lower dependency rates.
In East Asia, this "demographic dividend 'is the cause of more than a quarter of economic growth in the region.
Developing countries have already invested heavily in relation to the young.
They are now better educated and healthier than previous generations.
Over 80% of children attend primary school, against 50% in 1970, and infant mortality has declined from over 10% to 6.5% during the same period.
But governments must not only invest in children, they should also begin to address the new generation of young people.
However, in countries where the vast majority of children complete primary education, few of them attend secondary school.
Young people account for half of new cases of HIV infection.
In the Middle - East and North Africa, a quarter of young people are unemployed.
All this raises difficult questions: What - which hinders access to secondary education?
Is - that illiteracy remains high at times, even at the end of primary school, or a lack of resources?
Why is it not more young people who know how to protect themselves against AIDS?
Why do businesses in these countries complain - they often lack of qualified labor when so many students find themselves unemployed at the University of output?
An effective policy towards youth based on three types of measures: more opportunities for success for young people, more skills and the offer of a second chance.
Governments need to provide more opportunities for success to young people in improving access and quality care and education.
It is only in secondary education that students take full advantage of primary education.
Yet many young people are ill prepared for secondary school, and places are scarce.
Employers today want highly skilled workers.
In countries as diverse as Algeria, Bangladesh, Brazil, China, Estonia and Zambia, qualifications and inadequate training are difficult obstacles.
If one wants to prevent young people from becoming stuck in jobs with no hope of promotion or simply do become unemployed, they must have access to better education and training that meets the needs of businesses.
Several countries are now trying to facilitate access to secondary education, particularly through conditional transfer programs' that can distribute allowances to poor families whose children attend school regularly.
These programs have increased the number of students in secondary schools in Mexico, Ecuador, Bangladesh and Cambodia.
But for these programs to work, it is necessary that students have the skills to enter the high school.
In Morocco, for example, over 80% of children complete a first cycle of education, but less than 20% reach the required level.
Measures are also needed to help young people make good decisions.
A government can not replace parents or the community, but it can encourage young people and their families to take charge.
With the right information and proper stimulation, young people will be better equipped to make decisions about their health and their future.
In Cameroon, for young people of the cities, a program on sexual health, Horizon Jeunes, allowed to increase their knowledge on the subject and change their behavior. Thus, the rate of young women reporting condom use increased from 58% to 76% in the group who completed the program.
Another example: the Dominican Republic, the enrollment rate in secondary schools increased when college students were informed of the amount of wages of those who had reached the end of their secondary education, an amount they had vastly under - estimated.
In Bangladesh, the assistance to female high school project gave financial support to girls aged 11 to 14 to continue their education and delay time of marriage.
Governments must also provide a 'second chance' to young people who have failed due to circumstances or poor choices.
The corresponding programs must be well designed, targeted and coordinated to provide adequate incentives to beneficiaries.
For example, in sub - Saharan Africa, thousands of young combatants - 100,000 in Sudan alone - hope to rebuild their lives in peace time, but they clearly need training and employment, as well as medical care and psychological support.
With political will, measures based on young people's efforts self - to increase their chances of success and skills, and providing a second chance to those who need them, these countries could make the most of their demographic advantage.
They can either seize this growth opportunity to improve their development prospects, or take the risk of a lost generation embittered by the lack of future.
