Five years have passed since the terrorist attacks of September 2001 on New York and Washington, and yet it seems that policymakers have learned little about the modus operandi of terrorist cells and their weaknesses.
The Bush administration still uses the phrase "war against terror" and behaves as if it really was a usual type of war in which a government fights another.
However, after five years of military exertions, strategies based on targeting a united aggressor have only made the situation worse.
It is time to understand the new model of conflict emerging.
