In reality, there is no master planner or funder of terrorist activities.
The attacks in Madrid, Bali and London, as well as several thwarted States - States and Great - Britain, were all characterized by their dispersed organization.
These plots generated independently who have used ad hoc resources, often within the target country.
These small operations also lacked a common internal design.
Terrorist motivations differ from cell to cell, even from person to person.
Individuals can be motivated by profit or lust for power, or for political and religious reasons, while others participate for hate or for the thrill.
In addition, there are large differences in terms of risks, rewards, and imperatives as one climbs the organizational chain, or changing from one cell to another.
Conventional military models are geared to decapitate something that, in this case, has no head.
The characteristics of this new structure have already been studied in a very different context.
Terrorism is a violent version of an "agile virtual enterprise."
