The interventionist syndrome.
Kosovo often plays the role of conflict - to test the concept of intervention "humanitarian".
But as Iraq spirals into chaos, diplomats and leaders everywhere are again asking themselves if it is appropriate for alliances of nations or the international community to intervene when a sovereign country appears unable or unwilling to defend its citizens against genocide, war crimes and ethnic cleansing.
Central to this debate is the so-called doctrine of the "responsibility to protect".
As a mediator appointed by the Kosovo Nations - United in the last five years I have had the unique opportunity to observe the effects of that doctrine following NATO's intervention in the former Yugoslavia in 1999.
Kosovo has become an international experiment in society building, led by Interim Administration Mission to the UN in Kosovo (UNMIK).
Experience is the right word here.
Indeed, Kosovo has turned into a test tube of international intervention.
I lived and worked long enough in Kosovo to see the outcome, and I contend that such experiments require further research.
It is clear that the need for international intervention in a crisis depends on each specific period, and rapid response is often required.
However, apart from military factors, where such intervention is being considered it is of vital importance to focus international policy discussion on the rapid deployment of a civilian presence and security related to each other.
This is even more true when human suffering is caused by communal conflict, as was the case in Kosovo.
The immediate deployment of a civilian presence and adequate safety directly after the end of the 1999 NATO bombing could have provided suitable protective mechanisms against the backlash that allowed victims to become perpetrators.
NATO peacekeeping forces were not directed to stop the abductions, disappearances, revenge killings and massive destruction of property by ethnic Albanians, which led to a vast ethnic cleansing inverted population of non - Albanian (mainly Serb).
Consequence of this neglect, noxious social and political residue pervades today's Kosovo.
Instead of cooling communal conflict, interethnic hatred remains as heated as ever.
Besides the lack of a civil and security presence to reassure every community, the general lack of legal mechanisms to deliver swift justice for crimes committed during and after the intervention created additional tension.
This tension is so pervasive, in fact, that any chance of even beginning the much-needed reconciliation process must now be pushed far into the future.
Similarly, in Kosovo the international community has devoted little time to helping former combatants contemplate their collective responsibility for atrocities, their personal involvement was direct or indirect.
Without such an effort, attempting to improve the situation is like building a house on a pile of sand.
This lack of foresight and planning for the aftermath of armed intervention is not only dangerous for the people officially "saved" is also against - productive.
Unless a humanitarian intervention is not structured to ensure basic security, antagonisms sub - underlying that inspired the intervention to the database is only strengthened, not undermined.
Six years after the NATO intervention, Kosovo seems further than ever stability and social peace.
Despite the assurances of UN authorities that Kosovo is on the path of reconciliation and true autonomy, NATO officials indicate that there are plans to maintain a long-term military presence in the province in order to "guarantee that the political process will be implemented successfully".
This brings me to another key point: a possible exit strategy is as important to the success of any future humanitarian intervention as the entry strategy.
To that international intervention is a real chance to succeed, it must at the outset to define the criteria of "success".
Only such clarity can allow for a proper end to international actors' engagement.
In Kosovo, such clarity is and failed; accordingly, NATO and the UN have no clear idea about when or how they should both retire.
Someone once rightly said that it is easy to bomb, but much harder to build; it is relatively easy to defeat a regime militarily, but it is much more difficult to build a strong and sustainable civil society in its place.
The General Assembly of Nations - UN should keep this in mind as it starts to codify the doctrine of the "responsibility to protect".
