The long-term economic progress comes mainly from the invention and spread of improved technologies.
The scientific revolution was made possible by the printing press, the industrial revolution by the steam engine, and India's escape from famine, thanks to the increase in agricultural yields, the so-called " Green Revolution. "
The era of globalization we live emerged with the spread of computers and the Internet.
So when we seek solutions to some of the world's toughest problems, we can also find, at least in part, in new technologies to solve old seemingly intractable problems.
Take the example of poverty in Africa.
All possible explanations have been advanced, and usually focusing on what Africans do wrong.
But a visit to Africa's villages makes clear that the problem is more related to the struggle for survival under difficult physical conditions than with any special problems that are unique to African societies.
African farmers produce roughly one-third (or less) of food per hectare less than other world operators, which results in a large-scale famine, exacerbated by a heavy disease burden.
Malaria is a unique challenge of its kind, mainly due to the mosquito species in Africa, especially adept at transmitting the disease.
Other tropical parasitic diseases are extraordinary burdens on the continent.
Add - to the practical difficulty represented by poor roads and few cars and trucks, and economic isolation follows.
The challenges of survival are enormous.
Yet practical solutions are at hand, because simple and low-cost technologies can address specific problems.
We can overcome the low agricultural yields through improved seed varieties specially adapted for African conditions, combined with technologies for replenishing soil and managing water.
Malaria can be controlled through new nets to long life and a new generation of effective medicines.
Other tropical diseases also can be controlled, and practical technologies for safe drinking water can dramatically reduce diarrheal diseases.
Mobile phones, local wireless Internet, and more paved roads could do much to break the economic isolation of Africa's villages.
Donor countries incessantly ask Africans to change their trade policies, governmental institutions, governments, and more.
Some of these changes are important, but rich countries sometimes out of their roles, focusing on everything except how to finance and introduce practical technologies to solve practical problems.
The rich countries' mistakes would not matter if African countries had enough money to adopt the needed technologies on their own, but Africa is so poor that need financial help to get out of poverty.
Development challenges in Africa are just one example of how tough societal problems can be solved through the design and dissemination of improved technologies.
The same will be valid for the choice to be made in the best way to solve the problem of climate change caused by humans - another of those seemingly intractable global problems.
For now, rich countries are changing the world's climate by emitting billions of tons of carbon dioxide each year from the use of coal, oil and natural gas.
In the coming years, China and India will also contribute significantly to increased carbon dioxide levels in the atmosphere.
Yet no country, rich or poor, is keen to reduce its energy consumption, worried about such a move would threaten jobs, incomes and economic growth.
New technologies will provide a key part of the solution.
Already, "hybrid" automobiles, which combine gasoline and battery power, can roughly double fuel efficiency and halve emissions of carbon dioxide.
In addition, engineers have developed fishing techniques and store it safely underground carbon dioxide from the combustion of coal in power plants.
This new technology can reduce by 80% the emission of carbon dioxide during the production of electricity.
The costs are relatively modest.
Consider also the depletion of ocean-fishing.
The global demand for fish is increasing, and the global fishing capacity, threatening some species with extinction.
Improved aquaculture, in which fish are raised in ponds and reservoirs is still far from being a perfect technology, mainly for environmental reasons, yet it is very promising.
During a recent visit to Africa, a leading agronomist said that in today's world, the scientist is closer than ever before to the farmer, but farther away than ever from the legislator.
Politicians do not understand science, and rarely seek the advice of scientists and engineers in addressing major issues.
Everything is seen in terms of politics and elections, and nothing is considered as technical problems requiring technological expertise, which is why Africa's poverty is so often attributed to corruption rather than ecological challenges.
It's easy to dismiss the suggestion that technology can be the solution.
After all, technological advance also requires good governance, market forces, effective universities, and more.
Politics will also play a role.
Anyway, it's time to recognize that governments are ill-equipped to understand the sophisticated technological challenges and opportunities facing the world could benefit, and that new methods are needed to ensure that we give to science and technology necessary position to tackle a wide range of global issues taking a character more and more urgent.
It is now time that all the major international agencies and governments take the responsibility to use scientific and technological expertise that they will need in the twenty-first century.
