The moral of the death penalty.
A frequent criticism of states - united their refusal to abolish the death penalty.
Many now claim that abolition of capital punishment is a precondition of a civilized system of criminal law.
The Nobel laureate Gary Becker is not of this opinion.
European governments are adamantly opposed to capital punishment - the European Union bans it outright, and some Europeans consider its use to the States - United succession barbarism.
In fact, many European intellectuals argue that capital punishment, but punishment in general, does not deter criminals.
But while the Europeans, with crime rates well below those of States - States in the last half - century, could long afford to be relatively "gentle" with regard to most crimes, he saw their crime rates increase sharply during the past twenty years.
In contrast, American rates have fallen in part due to the increased use of punishment.
Capital punishment is one.
I am for the execution of some people convicted of murder because, and for that reason alone, I think it deters other murders.
If I did not believe that, I would oppose capital punishment, because revenge and other possible motives should not be a basis for public policy.
Serious empirical research on capital punishment in the States - States began with a study by Isaac Ehrlich, published in 1975 in the American Economic Review.
Some studies that have followed have sometimes found a much weaker deterrent effect, others a much stronger effect.
However, the available data are quite limited, so it should not base any conclusions solely on the econometric evidence.
Obviously punishment in terms of public policy can not expect perfect evidence.
But even with the limited quantitative evidence available, good reasons to believe in the deterrent effect of capital punishment is sufficient.
Most people, and murderers in particular, fear death, especially when it follows swiftly and with the commission of a murder.
As David Hume put it in discussing suicide, "no man ever threw away life, while it was worth living.
This is our natural horror of death "... Likewise, Schopenhauer believed that" when the horrors of life reach the point at which they outweigh the terrors of death, a man puts an end to his life.
But the terrors of death offer considerable resistance "...
Opponents of capital punishment frequently proclaim that the state has no moral right to take anyone's life would be - that that of the most reprehensible murderer.
Yet it is a conclusion quite wrong to think that the death penalty is a deterrent.
To see why, suppose that for each murderer executed (instead of, say, be sentenced to life in prison) the number of murders is reduced by three, which is a much lower number than Ehrlich and other estimates of the deterrent effect.
This implies that for each murderer not yet executed, three innocent victims would die.
In fact, the government would "take" indirectly many lives if it did not resort to the death penalty.
Saving three innocent lives for every person executed seems like a very attractive, and even two lives saved per execution seems like a cost / benefit persuasive for the death penalty.
However, it must be admitted that the argument in favor of capital punishment becomes less clear when the number of lives saved per execution falls.
But even if one life were saved per execution, the market may still be desirable if the life saved is much better than the life, which is generally the case.
Many people object to comparing the quality of life spared and that which is deleted.
Yet I do not see how to avoid such a comparison.
Take the case of a career criminal who robs and kills a victim who led a decent life and left several children and a spouse behind.
Suppose it is possible to save the life of an innocent victim by executing a criminal like this.
It seems to me that saving the life of such a victim must outweigh take life of the criminal.
Obviously, not all cases are not as clear, but a comparison of the qualities of individual lives must be part of any reasonable social policy.
This is also why the death penalty should be used only for murders, and not for lesser crimes.
When it comes to choosing between taking lives and, say, reducing property theft, the more lenient punishment of the thesis is much more powerful.
Although severe assaults, including some gruesome rapes, may approach some murders in severity, and might conceivably call for capital punishment, I'm not for use in such cases.
One argument for reserving capital punishment for murders is "marginal deterrence."
If assault were punished with the death penalty, would push the attackers to kill their victims to avoid discovery (which is a major reason for the severity of the punishment is proportionate to the gravity of the crimes).
One complication, however, could be a murderer fight over pugnacity to avoid being captured, which could lead to more deaths.
But, while marginal deterrence is important, I believe the resistance of murderers to being captured, possibly at the expense of their own lives, is really indirect evidence that criminals do fear capital punishment.
Of course, the risk of executing the innocent concern.
My support for capital punishment would weaken greatly if the rate of killing innocent people were as large as many claim.
However, I believe that the appeal process in the States - United offers enormous protection, not so much against wrongful conviction as against wrongful execution, which means that there is very little, if at all, case of executed people it is proved that they were innocent.
And this has been strengthened enormously with the development of DNA identification.
I say again that the debate on the death penalty is a debate on the power of deterrence (which may be reduced by lengthy appeals).
I can understand that some people are skeptical about the evidence, although I think they are wrong about this as well as on the question of common sense of the problem.
It is very disturbing to take someone's life, even that of a murderer, but sometimes highly unpleasant actions are necessary to prevent even worse behavior causing the death of innocent victims.
