Impose and spend (SVP).
Excessive taxation can dull incentives and hinder growth.
But insufficient taxation can also produce the same effects.
Governments with meager tax revenues can not provide basic public goods.
Worse yet, low tax revenues in poor countries often the result of shortcomings in the tax collection systems (rather than low tax rates) that also promote non-productivity.
India illustrates the importance of a well-designed tax system.
In Bangalore, high-tech companies have built world-class campus teeming with manicured lawns and ultra data communication networks - faster.
Outside these campuses, however, lie open sewers, uncollected garbage, and roads in disrepair.
Whereas technology companies instantaneously transmit terabytes of data to remote continents, local transport proceeds at an almost medieval pace.
Therefore, businesses in Bangalore run their own bus services, sub - contract with private suppliers for drinking water, and install generators to protect against power failures.
The state can not fix the shambles because it is broke.
Government debt in India exceeds 70% of GDP, so that more than half of its tax revenues go to paying interest.
But the debt is not the result of excessive spending in the past.
Government spending in India account for about 15% of GDP, against an average of about 40% of OECD GDP.
The financial difficulties of India rather because a tax system poorly designed and managed.
The rates and rules for taxes on individual and corporate income taxes appear reasonable by international standards.
Nevertheless, the government of India imposes taxes on income accounting for only about 3.7% of GDP, about half that of South Korea and other Asian tigers.
Agriculture in India accounts for about a quarter of GDP, but even wealthy farmers do not pay taxes.
Exporting companies in the software and other industries industry benefit from a tax holiday on their profits, although their employees pay taxes on their personal income.
Despite reasonable rates, tax evasion is widespread.
Fraud is explained by the fact that the government has not invested in personnel or in the systems to detect tax evaders, who rarely go to prison and that can often get out of pots pouring matter - of - wine when they are caught.
Even more subtly, the loophole taxes "direct" on incomes and profits reflects the mess to the "indirect" system of taxes levied on the production and consumption.
Excise taxes account for over 60% of indirect taxes in India, which in turn represent the same proportion of its total tax revenue.
The right to basic excise duty was fixed at 16% of the production value of a company.
Then follow various discounts, exemptions and surcharges.
For example, a "duty rate concessional" of 8% is levied on categories like food products, matches, cotton son and computers.
A "special excise duty" Additional 8% is levied on products that include polyester filament, cars, air conditioners and tires.
A "right of additional excise duty" (not to be confused with the "special excise duty") is levied on "goods of special importance."
The exemptions from excise duties are many and complex, including businesses with total annual revenues of less than 10 million rupees and firms located in certain troubled or backward areas.
Generally, exemptions are divided into 70 major categories, they - same sub - divided into 259 entries, 52 conditions, and 7 lists, each containing many elements.
Exemptions encourage abuse.
For a price, officials at the bottom of the hierarchy, which shows considerable discretion in applying the conditions, can be induced to give favorable interpretations.
Products taxed at high rates (for example, polished granite) are sold as goods taxed at lower rates (for example, as unpolished granite).
Evasion of excise taxes is more contagious than evasion on profits and revenues.
If a company fraud excise duties and the tax rate is high compared to pre-tax profits in the industry, its competitors also have to cheat just to survive.
While fraud increases, governments levy "additional" or "special" rights inciting further evasion.
Perceptions of direct taxes also suffer.
The pot - of - Wine paid to the collector of excise duty for a favorable classification, the difference between the value of polished and unpolished granite, and the real income underreporting create "black" funds that can not not be reported on income tax forms.
In addition to weaken the ability of the state to provide essential public goods, systems to evade indirect taxes also discourage businesses from adopting more productive technologies, which requires technologies involving a large-scale deployment .
But as indirect taxes can be more easily bypassed by deploying several small units instead of one large unit, it is impossible to achieve economies of scale.
It is important to note that in the software industry, where all units are exempt from indirect taxes, Indian companies operate at efficient scale.
India could - it follow the example of China, the country where the rationalization of indirect taxes in 1994 set the stage for a great boom?
Or coalition governments in a vigorous democracy are - they are incapable of such reform?
Last year, the government led by the BJP of India has enacted legislation allowing for substantial reductions in the budget deficit.
He then appointed a task force to formulate the necessary changes to the policies of public spending and tax policies.
Last July, the task force proposed raising taxes (rather than cutting spending) by removing most indirect tax exemptions, among other things.
The new government led by the Congress of India also seems to favor these proposals.
If Congress and the opposition parties follow, they will help a lot to support the country's economic growth and in dispelling the idea that democracies can not take the necessary measures to encourage development.
