The value of European values.
European leaders have taken the constitutional discussions that ended last December following a dispute about voting rights.
These debates are obviously lead to compromise, which will be soon.
Remains to understand clearly what the supposed objectives of the Constitution.
Two fundamental principles guided European integration: solidarity and subsidiarity.
These two principles are at the crossroads of philosophy, politics, economics, sociology and law.
For years, they have been an integral part of the legal and institutional structure of the European Union in the Treaties, the Charter of Fundamental Rights (which quotes them in the Preamble) and in the recent avant - draft Constitution.
In short, they are recorded in the history and the EU ideals.
But what is the real significance of these two principles?
Consider solidarity, which is open to two interpretations minimum: static solidarity, which concerns only the distribution of income and wealth, and the broader concept of dynamic solidarity, which concerns the production of income and wealth.
In the history of post - war European integration, dynamic solidarity was strongly manifested during the first period, that of the European Coal and Steel Community, both in its economic development strategy (reconstruction ) than in the Treaties, particularly the Treaty of Rome.
This does not mean that dynamic solidarity was subsequently suppressed by: the European Monetary Union, for example, perfectly expresses this principle.
Thus, although some countries did not immediately benefit from the euro, they nevertheless accepted because they were convinced that it would have positive effects on the long term.
In other words, the dynamic solidarity means promote policies that encourage investment, innovation, economic growth and employment.
However, as indicated GDP growth in the EU, dynamic solidarity has been undermined over the last decade.
The gap between research and development is of particular concern.
The implementation of the so - called Lisbon Strategy of the EU, adopted in 2000 with the promise to create the most competitive economy in the world, is threatened by the growing emphasis on static solidarity, reflected the high cost of welfare and high taxes needed to finance it.
The primacy of static solidarity is due to an aging population, along with slower growth, has led to structural fiscal imbalances.
One of the biggest challenges to the future of the EU is to address the current prevalence of static solidarity, which is geared towards the elderly, at the expense of dynamic solidarity, which promotes youth.
After all, the Union can not allow the current consumption continues to prevail over the investment needed for future prosperity.
Subsidiarity is similar to the concept of solidarity in that its interpretation is twofold: the vertical subsidiarity and horizontal subsidiarity.
Vertical subsidiarity concerns the distribution of powers between the different levels of government and sovereignty: the EU, national states, regions and municipalities.
The best known application of this principle is federalism.
The European treaties clearly express this vertical subsidiarity.
But - it enough to encompass the emerging institutional and constitutional framework of the Union?
Horizontal subsidiarity concerns the responsibility and freedom of human beings as well as social and economic powers.
It encompasses the relations between state, society and the market.
But society and the market have their own rights and their own sovereignties that are not granted by the state.
Then there arises the following problem: how to ensure the autonomy of each realm?
An example of horizontal subsidiarity internal European market, which has created a new kind of economic freedom and increased competition between businesses by eliminating the protection as national governments offered them.
Horizontal subsidiarity means that in society and in the economy, the state can not violate individual freedom and responsibility, which must be observed at the highest possible level.
It also implies that a "higher power" must support whenever individual freedom and responsibility are not enough to achieve the goals necessary for human dignity.
