The end of the secret.
Transparency is not always an easy exercise in the new democracies of Eastern Europe. This was discovered Hungarian Prime Minister Ferenc Gyurcsany, when a recording in which he admitted the lies of the government sparked riots.
Such as Hungary, Romania post - communist endeavored to encourage openness and honesty in a society that once numbered among the most closed in the world.
But the persistence of a culture of secrecy blew corruption and abuse of power.
We note however a real evolution towards more transparency, evolution recognized by the European Union has given the green light to Romania for membership in early 2007.
In addition to the introduction of what the EU stands today for a "functioning market economy" essential reforms in the political and legal, which I am responsible, range from increased transparency and control the financing of political parties to the reorganization of the judiciary.
Judicial reforms contribute to root out corruption.
Ministers and former ministers, parliamentarians, judges, lawyers, and members of the police, customs and other public bodies, as well as private entrepreneurs have been indicted.
In addition, new forms have been developed for wealth declarations and financial interests by those in official positions in government, parliament, public and local administration and the judiciary.
The new reporting procedures are the most detailed in Europe, and above all they are made public.
Progress of Romania are confirmed by a report published this month - one, that citizens of Eastern Europe now have access to government information as well as those of the established democracies of long standing.
The Transparency and Silence report of the Open Society Justice Initiative (available on www.justiceinitiative.org) even shows that new democracies are sometimes better than the old: some Romanian government bodies more responsive to requests for information from citizens their French or Spanish counterparts.
Specifically, 60% of requests are in Romania, against 31% in France and 24% in Spain.
Other good performers include Peru and Mexico, two countries that have adopted legislation on freedom of information in 2002, shortly after Romania.
Yet it is not always easy to access sensitive information in transitional democracies.
I worked as a lawyer for the defense of human rights in the Romanian Helsinki Committee, and we often had to go to court to demand the release of information under Romanian law 2001 Freedom information.
For example, when we officially gained access to data on wiretaps authorized by the Attorney General, he simply ignored the decision.
We attacked civilian, and the judge imposed a fine for each day of delay in reporting.
Only when the media became interested in the case, that the data - number of eavesdropping during the previous ten years, those affected and duration of operations - were released.
Romania then finally started to turn his back on a past marked by the omnipresence of the Securitate.
I am now part of the government, and I realize that it is not always easy to share some information with the public.
But sometimes painful reforms are necessary.
We would not have carried out economic and political reforms that will allow us to enter the EU without subjecting our policies to public scrutiny and without accepting increased citizen participation in decision-making that inevitably accompanies such opening.
In fact, access to information has become a sine qua non of democracy around the world.
When the United - States have adopted the Freedom of Information Act in 1966, they were the only ones, with Sweden and Finland.
Today, 65 countries have such legislation.
In Romania, those who fought for the adoption of a law on freedom of information taking full advantage.
According to the study of the Justice Initiative, the people who come to the Romanian government receive little difficulty the information it would have been unthinkable to communicate it a few years ago.
Thus, the Romanian Ministry of Defence has disclosed the number of soldiers who died in 2003, and the circumstances (including 13 suicides, two deaths by gunfire, and two combat deaths in Afghanistan).
Another example, the Bucharest Tribunal received a request for the number of judges is the subject of a disciplinary procedure from the beginning of 2000, and reasons for possible sanctions.
The court forwarded the request to the Superior Judicial Council, which gave a complete answer: four pages listing all sanctioned judges, motives and actions.
This process is both the result and the motor of continuing reform.
The rulers have not always been very comfortable with the opening, and the battle continues for the most sensitive documents.
But in the former communist countries, the benefits of transparency are undeniable.
Yet the experience of Romania shows that official secrecy remains a threat, no country is safe, and that only a vigilance of every moment can prevent it from undermining the foundations of democracy .
Save the trees of life.
No one can finish the day without using a derivative of the forest.
In a larger extent than is generally believed, the paper on which is written, the water flowing from our taps, drugs that treat us, the wood that our homes and our furniture is made all come from the forest .
Forests give us fresh air we breathe and are home to endangered species.
They also provide us with recreational areas, which is becoming increasingly important in our complex world.
About 1.5 billion people living in poor rural areas depend directly on forests for their basic needs for food and firewood.
Yet deforestation continues.
Every year, we lose 14.6 million hectares of forest, an area almost as large as four times Switzerland.
Irresponsible forest management, enhanced by regulations and weak government bonds, and markets that reward illegal logging all conspire to deprive the world of its most valuable and threatened forests.
When the forests start to disappear, a host of environmental, social and economic problems usually follow, affecting us all in one way or another.
The island of Sumatra in Indonesia is a good example.
The pulp and paper companies are undertaking a rampant and illegal destruction of forests that contain the greatest diversity of plants in the world.
It is likely that as yet unknown plants disappear in the process just as endangered species such as rhinos and Sumatran elephant and the orang - utan.
When the forest of Sumatra have disappeared, entire communities are also left without appropriate places to live and no decent way to make a living.
In addition, the distortion that trade in illegal products and cheap products to world markets is necessary because of difficulties for responsible citizens.
Developing countries are losing $ 15 billion in tax revenues annually due to illegal logging.
To complicate matters, the demand for wood for reconstruction following the tsunami last year, has intensified an already unsustainable demand vis - a - vis the Sumatran forests.
The basins of the Amazon and the Congo are subject to similar threats.
A recent United Nations study, the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment (MA), shows that forests and other important regions are in serious decline due to mismanagement and will continue to disappear unless serious protection measures are not in place.
Information published by the Brazilian government show that deforestation of irreplaceable forests in the Amazon, from agricultural conversion, reached 2.6 million hectares last year, bringing the total deforested area of Amazon to 17%.
Yet the battle against deforestation is not yet lost.
Different organizations, movements and defense companies concerned about the state of the world's forests are working together to reverse the phenomenon of deforestation and improve forest management.
Thus, for example, WWF (World Wildlife Fund) and the World Bank helped the Brazilian government to launch an initiative to establish new forest protection areas on more than 17 million hectares in the form of national parks.
The cooperation of WWF and the World Bank has also motivated other partners to establish a trust fund to manage these protected areas in perpetuity.
Similarly, a summit meeting of the leaders of the countries of the Congo Basin has enabled cross-border cooperation for forest conservation and responsible management.
All this led eventually to release $ 53 million from the State Department of States - States to promote conservation of Congo's forests.
Since the first meeting of leaders in 1999, 3.5 million hectares of protected areas were newly organized in the Congo Basin.
However, given the consequences of the Asian tsunami last December, the weight of evidence provided by the EM and statistics on deforestation of the most critical areas, we must continue our efforts.
The World Bank and WWF recently pledged to work towards the reduction of 10% of the global deforestation rate for 2010 and work with the institutions of the public and private sectors to enable ambitious achievements in forest conservation.
WWF studies show that if the world's forests are shared between different uses, including the protection of certain areas, responsible business management and forest landscape restoration, we can meet the world's needs for forest products while maintaining environmental values ‚Äã‚Äãand Social critical to our near future.
Business leaders, governments, civil society organizations must all play their part in achieving this vision.
The Saudis are - they fanatic?
Terrorist attacks in Saudi Arabia have led many to question the prospects for survival of the ruling House of Saud and the question whether the kingdom is fundamentally dysfunctional and destructive or not.
For one reason or another, it seems that Saudi society has produced a stream of violent fanaticism that draws its inspiration from extreme religious orthodoxy.
The fact that 15 of the 19 hijackers who took part in the attacks of 11 September 2001 against the United - States were Saudis crystallized a long-held view of the kingdom as a bastion of authoritarianism and intolerance .
In some respects, this perception is correct, but it can not be applied to the Saudi population as a whole.
On the contrary, it would be a grave mistake to assume that fanatical Islamism fully defines Saudi attitudes toward religion.
Between 2001 and 2003, I was part of a team to achieve a large-scale study of values ‚Äã‚Äãin Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Iran and Jordan.
Our results provide a surprisingly nuanced picture of Saudi attitudes.
Compared with respondents living in other countries in the Middle - East, the Saudis have proved the least religious of all in general, and their attitudes toward democracy and arranged marriage also indicate a sense sub - underlying moderate.
It is certain that in the four countries, religiosity is widespread, more than 90% of respondents collectively reporting that they believe in God, in life after death, and heaven and hell.
But the Saudis appear to be less religious than their fellow Muslims.
Seventy - two percent of Saudis described themselves as religious individuals, against 82% of Iranians, 85% of Jordanians and 98% of Egyptians.
Americans also appear to be more religious than Saudis, with 81%.
This variation can be partly explained by cross-national differences on the meaning of "religiosity".
For example, Americans may define religiosity differently than people in the Middle - East with can - be less pronounced attachment to religious beliefs in Islamic countries.
This might also account in part for the differences between Muslim countries.
But the gap between the Saudis on one side and Iranians, Jordanians and Egyptians another in self-defined religiosity is so great that it challenges the prevalent perception of Saudi Arabia as a highly conservative and religious .
Indeed, actions speak louder than words: only 28% of Saudis said they attended religious services weekly, against 27% of Iranians, 44% of Jordanians, 42% of Egyptians and 45% of Americans.
These findings, while running contrary to popular perceptions of Saudi culture, are less startling than they appear.
Sociologists of religion have long argued that in a monolithic religious environment, or when religious institutions are closely linked to the state, the overall religiosity of the public declines.
It makes sense to think that when state authorities enforce strict codes of behavior, people tend to rebel and move away from officially sanctioned religious institutions.
It is thus hardly surprising that Egyptians and Jordanians, who live in countries where the state does not enforce piety, are more religious than Iranians or Saudis, who must deal with the police " Under "locale supported by the state.
Even on the issue of marriage, many Saudis expressed surprisingly liberal views.
The respondents were split almost evenly on the question of arranged marriages, with half supporting the idea that marriage should be based on parental consent, against 48% who considered love as the basis of marriage.
Since gender segregation and paternal dominance firmly anchored, this result seems to reveal a strong desire to greater individual choice in what has been traditionally a family decision.
Finally, the Saudis turn out strong supporters of democracy, contradicting again the widespread image of Saudi conservatism.
All Saudis polled, 58% considered democracy the best form of government that is, 23% disagreed and 18% were not expressed.
The massive support for democracy in a country without secular and nationalist history seems against - intuitive.
In fact, support for democracy corresponds to several other liberal attitudes that we found in Saudi Arabia.
Supporters of democracy tend to be less religious, more secular, more tolerant of others, more critical of public sector shares and more worried by the Western cultural invasion.
To - beyond the study data, history has shown that liberal ideas become more popular when a despotic monarch governs with the support of a religious institution.
A strong current of liberalism appeared in the late nineteenth century in Ottoman Syria in response to the religious despotism of Sultan Abdulhamid.
At the same time, a secular movement anti - clerical behalf of constitutionalism appeared in Iran in reaction to the absolutist alliance between the shahs Quajar and religious institution.
In light of the similarities between those historical precedents and current conditions in Saudi Arabia, we should not rule out reform.
The study data also suggest that Saudis may well require a more transparent policy and a less interventionist religion.
