A practical guide to the Israeli hawks.
The announcement of Prime Minister Ariel Sharon indicating its willingness to dismantle Jewish settlements in Gaza and some West Bank settlements has shocked and unprepared the Israeli nation and nations around the world.
Many denounced Sharon's plan as a stratg√®me.
But the surprise was crazy from the start.
Despite the appearance they give to foreigners, the debate in Israel about the future of the occupied territories have not been reduced to a simple story of hawks and doves.
Like everything in Israel, the process is more complex, especially where the hawks are concerned.
Overall, there are two species of Israeli hawks: the ideological and strategic.
Ideological hawks view the occupied territories as part of the historical Land of Israel, the homeland of the Jewish people.
For them, the territories covered by the Jewish heritage, which explains their insistence on calling the West Bank by its Hebrew historical appellation Judea and Samaria.
Ideological hawks are not all religious, although those who are base their claim on divine promises and prophecies.
But many ideological hawks are secular nationalists, and their jargon is similar to that of nationalist types of Eastern Europe and Central Europe.
Former Prime Minister Menachem Begin and Yitzhak Shamir belonged to that category.
Ideological hawks usually belong to the National Religious Party and the Likud.
They are inspired by a nationalist ideology associated with Vladimir Jabotinsky, who founded Zionism "revisionist" to challenge the more moderate version adopted by the Founding Fathers of Israel, including Chaim Weizmann and David Ben - Gurion.
Then there are the strategic hawks.
For them, given the narrow and vulnerable geographic shape of Israel and the continued hostility of the Arabs, the control of the West Bank and Gaza is not an ideological imperative, but responds to security considerations.
For them, Jewish settlements in the territories are not a return to historical lands, but represent security strongholds to prevent (or to push for a more strategic location) a heart attack Israel.
This assessment of the situation may be right or wrong, but it certainly is not ideological.
Ariel Sharon, who comes from a military background (he grew up in a social environment in which ideas were more akin to the Labour Party as those of Jabotinsky) is a strategic hawk.
For ideological hawks, compromises are treason: how to jeopardize the historical patrimony of the Jewish people, let alone God's promise to Abraham?
Strategic hawks, however, are open to negotiations and practical compromises, if circumstances are favorable and if the security considerations justify it in their eyes.
It is in this context that must be considered the actions of Sharon.
He was elected on the promise that he would bring peace and security.
He has brought neither one nor the other.
With the defeat and demise of Saddam Hussein, the danger of an "Eastern front" against Israel has weakened.
No Palestinian partner, and because of the ongoing Palestinian terrorism fierce Israeli actions fail to suppress the actions of Sharon flow from this strategy oriented thinking: build an effective barrier, move some of the isolated settlements and strategically untenable, and wait.
Sharon's statements in the previous year seem to follow a well-defined model.
First, he admitted "that one day or another," a Palestinian state would make its appearance, an inconceivable idea for pure ideological hawks.
A few months later, he scandalized his followers at the conference of the Likud party, declaring that the occupation was unacceptable and untenable, another shock for those who always talked about "liberated" territories rather than "occupied" territories.
Last December, he explicitly stated that Israel had turned to a cease - - unilateral ceasefire that would inevitably lead to the "relocation" of some settlements.
Although these statements were similar again to a simple verbiage, they have nevertheless created a new language for a Likud prime minister.
The latest statements of Sharon nevertheless explicitly named the settlements to be evacuated; Director of the National Security Council, Giora Eiland General, was appointed chairman of an inter relocation committee to develop plans to evacuate settlements and to provide compensation for relocated settlers.
All this has radically altered the internal political map of Israel.
Some ideological hawks in Sharon's government threatened to resign; Shimon Peres announced that Labour would give Sharon a parliamentary safety net; it is also talk that the Labor Party to join a national unity government.
The test is obviously not the planning, but the implementation of withdrawal, and the road is long and bumpy.
Timing Sharon may have been guided by his problems with police investigations after its alleged corruption.
However, anyone wishing to predict the future behavior of Sharon must keep in mind that unlike Begin and Shamir, Sharon has a military background and that for him, security, not ideology, comes first .
His apparent pragmatism should thus come as no surprise.
