Fight against drugs: we must change strategy.
Once again, Russia and Ukraine are victims of an illusion.
Since the end of communism in 1991, the use of prohibited drugs has increased dramatically in these two countries (as well as many others).
They have responded with draconian measures in line with the simplistic policy of total elimination of drugs adopted by the UN.
These measures are now contributing to the AIDS explosion in the number of developing countries.
UN conventions governing the fight against drugs policy at international level does not take into account the recent findings on drug use and dependence.
Most of these agreements were established well before the onset of AIDS is spread primarily through the use of intravenous drugs in the countries of the ex - Soviet Union and in many Asian countries.
Thus, at the international level, it is in Russia and Ukraine that AIDS is spreading the fastest.
The number of people infected has increased to 18 during the past five years.
An estimated one and a half million Russians and 400,000 Ukrainians are affected and 85% of them are intravenous drug users.
In a misguided attempt to comply with UN conventions, the Russian and Ukrainian governments use most of their means of struggle against drugs repression.
Drug users are victims of ill-treatment by the police and were turned down by the health services, even for vital care.
Meanwhile, drugs continue to flood the market.
In drug, repression has never succeeded in eliminating demand.
Repression takes into account either the economic and social factors, neither the public health concerns related to the use of banned substances.
Locking up drug users is not a solution; in Russia it is even easier to buy drugs in prison than outside.
In a repressive climate, drug users who escape arrest tend to be subject to discrimination, which does not encourage them to protect their health or that of those around them.
If the company offers no hope for addicts and shown no compassion for them, substance abuse and the AIDS virus can only develop rapidly.
Russia and Ukraine are not the only ones to cope with the increase in intravenous drug use and the spread of AIDS that accompanies it.
If they continue this type of policy, Pakistan, Iran, China, Central Asian countries and all the countries that are in the same situation will face the same disaster in terms of public health.
Numerous studies worldwide show that in the fight against drugs, the action in the field of public health is the most effective way to reverse the HIV infection and reduce expenditure.
The British medical journal Lancet estimated that the US would have saved at least $ 500 million if they had set up a needle exchange program at the national level during the period 1987-1995.
A survey conducted at international level shows that HIV infection decreased from 5.8% in cities where there is a needle exchange program, but it increased by 5.9% in cities where there is none.
No studies of importance only showed a correlation between the existence of a needle exchange program and an increase in drug abuse.
Studies undertaken in the USA, Australia, and elsewhere show that if the number of addicts who receive treatment does not decrease, it is because the participants in needle exchange programs will have easier access.
UN agencies such as the Commission on Drugs and the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC, ex - UNDCP) have no mandate to prescribe a specific fight against drugs strategy.
Nevertheless, their narrow conception of the fight against drugs has a strong influence on politics and the measures taken by states - members.
Many governments, obsessed with compliance with UN conventions, can not or do not want to take into account the negative effects in terms of public health of a strictly repressive policy against drugs.
In the 1990s, when AIDS began killing millions of people in Africa, infecting more than a quarter of the population of some countries, international institutions have turned away.
For similar reasons, this terrible epidemic is about to hit, among other countries of the ex - Soviet Union.
Have - we learned nothing?
It is not too late, policymakers at national and international level may still reconsider their strategy.
Despite the UN conventions, some countries have adopted a more pragmatic attitude towards drugs and AIDS.
Consider that it is primarily a public health issue helps fight much more effectively the AIDS epidemic.
The following measures would achieve it.
¬∑ Adopt anti - discrimination legislation to guarantee civil liberties and human rights of drug users and people living with HIV.
¬∑ Recognize that drug use is a public health problem and not of law enforcement or law enforcement and implement a policy that reflects this fact.
¬∑ Explicitly legalize needle exchange programs and methadone treatment and other alternatives.
¬∑ Establish national risk reduction programs that are pragmatic and accessible to all. This requires education, alternative therapies, detoxification programs and needle exchanges.
¬∑ Both nationally and internationally, to involve drug users and their advocates in the development of drug policy.
Refuse to reconsider the goals of the anti - drug and chosen strategies will only worsen the AIDS epidemic and contribute to the death of millions of vulnerable people.
Abandonment of the resolutions of Lisbon.
Upon taking office as President of the European Commission, Dur√£o Barroso - former Prime Minister of Portugal - will have to spend urgently reorganize and refocus economic policies of the European Union.
The thickest file that awaits is the resolutions of Lisbon, an ambitious program approved in 2000 by the Heads of State and Government of the European Union in order to make the EU "the the economy most competitive and dynamic "in 2010.
The main economic fields are covered: innovation and entrepreneurship, reform of social systems and social inclusion, skills and employment, gender equality at work, market liberalization of employment and property and sustainable development.
Certainly these are brave ambitions but which inherently belong to the sphere of national political decisions.
According to the European Treaties, the EU has no competence to establish a legislative and political arsenal in these areas, nor the power to enforce it.
However, the Council of Europe, encouraged by the European Commission, invented a new policy approach - called "open coordination" - in order to affect these areas.
Open coordination involves the determination of common goals at the EU, voluntary compliance by the Member States and internal control results in the Council of Europe.
Obviously, open coordination failed to keep its promises.
In addition, the illusion that the Council of Europe can somehow summon the growth and productivity has provided a diversion to national politicians who do not want to promote nationally unpopular decisions.
Thus, I suggest that Mr Barroso, at first, to get rid of the Lisbon agenda.
This is the only thing to do to make clear that national responsibilities remain in the hands of national politicians in economic performance.
This brings me to macroeconomic coordination in the European Union.
The Maastricht Treaty envisaged a simplified policy framework for monetary and economic union.
Monetary policy was centralized and entrusted to an independent central bank, while fiscal policy remains the responsibility of Member States.
National governments were subject to two constraints - depending on the excessive deficit procedure control - to prevent fiscal deficits above 3% of GDP and budget deficits of more than 60% of GDP (or at least around this value).
Thereafter, the Stability and Growth Pact added an additional criterion in the medium term, to ensure that national budgets are "almost balanced".
This was intended mainly to prevent irresponsible budgetary policies after the launch of the euro, while leaving sufficient room for cyclical oscillations of the deficit within the limit of 3%.
The credibility of this set of measures was greatly undermined by the November 2003 public controversy between the Commission and the Council of Ecofin on the implementation of the control procedure excessive budget deficits in France and Germany.
That does not mean it should be abandoned.
Instead, a common external constraint on fiscal behavior is needed as a guard - crazy together against an accumulation of unsustainable public debt, which could affect financial stability and inflation throughout the EU - an increased risk the impact of aging populations on pension systems.
Such a constraint also provides an anchor conducive to national decision-making in the Member States whose political systems are less reinforced.
But the system needs to be reviewed.
I do not listen to those who advocate excluding investment tax losses: this only provide further encouragement for creative accounting and unsustainable accumulation of debt.
Instead, we must focus on the sustainability of debt rather than annual deficits.
The criterion of debt, for example, could be accompanied by a limitation on (trends) growth rate of public expenditure, which would be kept below the rate of nominal GDP.
The Commission's power to initiate movement when there is risk of excessive deficits should be strengthened - as, of course, the Commission will never forget that monitoring of national policies is a task that requires a certain political sense and can not be left in the hands of managers and lawyers.
Finally, we must make European integration the main priority for the Union has at its disposal a powerful legal instrument to force open markets and strengthen competition.
The best therapy to stimulate growth must be both direct, by increasing competitive pressure, and indirect, by triggering the measures necessary for the adaptation of national employment policy, social protection and education.
This is where long-term effort.
State subsidies for enterprises in decline remain ambiguous and common laws designed to ensure the free movement of goods and services are not fully respected by Member States - public and energy markets are the best examples.
In addition, most service contracts - trade in securities, wholesale and retail distribution, business services, and local utilities - remain sheltered from competition and regulation free - trade.
The evidence is there to show that these market distortions services accounting for two-thirds of GDP are responsible for most of the productivity gap suffered by the EU vis - a - vis States - united.
In recent years, the Council of Europe has not devoted sufficient attention to these tasks, which involve a total and constant commitment by Member States to transpose and implement European directives.
All too often, the Commission has encouraged the development of new legislation and creating new spending programs rather than effective management of what is already in place.
So Barroso should forget the high-flying platitudes of the Lisbon agenda and focus instead on the effective implementation of the single market and put order in fiscal policies of the Member States.
You have to let local governments take responsibility for the economic performance of their country.
The emotional clash of civilizations.
