Globalization and anti - Americanism.
The anti - American sentiments are rising around the world.
American Democrats say that President Bush's policies have squandered America's attractiveness.
Republicans reply that America is bound to be resented because of its size and its association with globalization.
According to them, the anti - Americanism will persist because some people see America as a cultural threat.
Personally, I think these views lack historical perspective.
Contrary to conventional wisdom, globalization is not a factor of homogenization and Americanization of world cultures.
Although the United - States are at the forefront of the current information revolution, which allows the development of similarities in cultural and social behavior (such as television viewing or Internet use) that are attributed to the Americanization, although the correlation is not causation.
To understand why, imagine a country that introduced computers and communications at speed in a world where America would not exist.
One would expect still to cultural and social changes of importance because of such modernization.
Of course, because of the existence of the United - States and their presence at the cutting - edge of the information revolution, there is a degree of Americanization, which will likely decrease during the twenty-first century thanks to the technology spreads and local cultures modernize in their own time.
Historical proof that globalization does not necessarily mean homogenization is in Japan, a country that deliberately isolated from the rest of the world during the first waves of globalization.
In the mid - nineteenth century, Japan became the first Asian country to embrace globalization, and to borrow successfully from the world without losing its uniqueness.
During the Meiji Restoration, Japan searched broadly for tools and innovations that would allow it to become a leading power rather than a victim of Western imperialism.
He sent young people to study in Western societies.
Its delegations around the world in search of scientific innovation, technology and industry.
In the political realm, Meiji reformers were well aware of the philosophy and American institutions, yet they chose to turn to the German model they found more appropriate to a country ruled by an emperor.
The lesson that Japan teaches the rest of the world not only is that an Asian country can compete, but that after a century and a half of globalization, it is possible to adapt while preserving a unique culture.
Above all, the image of a homogenizing America reflects a mistakenly factor static view of culture.
Efforts to portray local cultures as unchanging often reflect reactionary political strategies rather than descriptions of reality.
In the words of the Peruvian writer Mario Vargas Llosa, those who defend cultural identities against globalization betray a stagnant attitude towards culture not borne out by historical component.
Have - we know of any cultures that have remained unchanged through time?
To find any of them, go to the small, primitive, magico - religious, populated by people who ... because of their primitive condition, become progressively more vulnerable to exploitation and extermination.
Vibrant cultures are constantly changing and borrowing from other cultures and that borrowing is not always from the United - States.
Thus, many countries turned to Canada than the United - States as an example to their own constitution in the years following the end of the Cold War.
Globalization is also a double-edged sword.
In some areas, not only the backlash is felt against American cultural imports, but an effort is also made to change American culture itself - even.
A majority of Americans probably agree with the death penalty today, but the death penalty is considered a gross violation of human rights throughout Europe, in fact, almost anywhere in the world.
US positions on the environment and climate change or GMOs bring similar criticism.
More subtly, America's openness to immigration as well enriches and changes American culture.
Finally, globalization and the information revolution may reinforce rather than reduce cultural diversity.
Some French commentators express fear that in a world of global Internet marketing that would leave no room for a culture that cherishes hundreds of different varieties of cheese.
On the contrary, the Internet allows dispersed customers to come together in order to encourage niche markets, and even hundreds of websites devoted exclusively to cheese.
The Internet also allows people to establish more diverse set of political communities.
The use of Welsh in Great - Britain and Gaelic in Ireland is greater today than it was there half - century.
Great - Britain, Belgium and Spain, among other European countries have granted greater powers to regional and local representatives.
The global information age may strengthen rather than weaken local cultures.
Economic and social globalization does produce superficial similarities in T logos - shirt or soft drink brands, but there will always be a great cultural diversity under - lying.
