Israeli politics is undergoing the most impressive changes he has seen in 30 years.
The realignment of parties and leaders is particularly noteworthy given the unexpected nature of recent events dated: Ariel Sharon's decision to leave the Likud, Peres's defeat as leader of the Labour Party and the withdrawal of the Labour Sharon's grand coalition government.
It is all the more crucial to understand the significance of these changes for the future of Israel, the region and the Arab - Israeli conflict.
Schematically, the Israeli political system is approaching the end of its second era.
From independence in 1948 until 1977, the Labour Party has dominated before giving way to an opposition coalition of conservative, nationalist, and centrist parties allied in the Likud bloc.
Since then, the two parties have held power alternately, sometimes in large coalitions and sometimes in partnership with smaller parties.
On the surface, the rivalry between parties was played between "left" and "right" or "hawks" and "doves."
The truth, of course, is more complex.
Social class and economic problems, in the shadow of more persistent existential concerns, such as physical security and continuity of the state, played a much less important role in Israel than in other societies.
Here, the political divide could be defined as the clash of "optimists" and "pessimists".
The first, Labour, believed that some day a force would emerge among Arabs and Palestinians ready to make peace on reasonable grounds, while the latter, Likud, were more circumspect.
For years, the discussion remained an abstraction, a debate over what might happen in the future, until the Oslo agreement with the PLO in 1993 will put to the test the competing visions.
Since 2000, when the PLO leader Yasser Arafat rejected a political agreement and began instead a terrorist war five years, there is little optimistic.
The intellectual realignment which resulted in Israel has given rise to a new national consensus.
It is now widely accepted that, as the left has always stressed, Israel must be prepared to withdraw from the West Bank and the Gaza Strip and accept a Palestinian state in exchange for real peace.
But it is also widely accepted that, as the right has always maintained, no partner is really ready to make peace.
In this context, Sharon won two landslide election victories as a radical while applying a moderate policy, including a full withdrawal from the Gaza Strip.
That is where Israel today, facing a political upheaval fueled by two developments.
