A moral power.
According to forecasts, global meat consumption is expected to double by 2020.
Yet in Europe and North America, we wonder more and more about the moral aspect of meat production methods and eggs.
Veal consumption has dropped since it became widely known that to produce so-called veal "white" (actually pale pink), calves new - born babies are separated from their mothers, anemic voluntarily deprived of fiber and packed in stalls so small that he can not walk or turn around.
In Europe, mad cow shocked many, not just because it has parts of the image healthy and safe food beef, but also because the public learned that the disease was caused by feeding cows fed sheep brains and nervous tissues.
People who naively believed that cows ate grass discovered that flocks for our food could eat anything from corn to fish, chicken litter (manure included) of slaughterhouse waste.
Concern about how we treat farm animals is far from being limited to the small percentage of vegetarians or vegans, who consume no animal products.
Despite strong ethical arguments for vegetarian practices, they do not represent the prevailing view.
The most common position is that our meat consumption is justified as long as the animals live a proper life before being killed.
The problem, as Jim Mason and I describe in our recent book, The Way We Eat, is that industrial agriculture denies animals a chance to have a proper life.
Tens of billions of chickens produced today never go out.
Are packaged so that they have a voracious appetite and gain weight as fast as possible and then raises them in sheds that can hold more than 20,000 animals.
The ammonia levels in the air, due to the accumulation of their droppings stings the eye and hurts the lungs.
Killed 45 days, their immature bones can hardly bear the weight of their bodies.
Some collapse and, unable to reach food or water, soon die. Their fate is only a negligible amount to the whole company of the economic ladder.
Conditions are even worse for laying hens crammed into cages son of iron, so small that even if they were only one per cage, they would be unable to open the wings.
But they are usually crowded by four, often more.
Under such crowded conditions, the more dominant, aggressive hens can sting the lowest in the cage to death.
To prevent this, producers sear off all birds' beaks with a hot blade.
The beak of a chicken is full of nerve tissue. It is, after all, her principal means of communication with its environment, but no anesthetic or analgesic is used to relieve pain.
Pigs may - be the most sensitive and intelligent animals we used to eat.
When foraging in a rural village, they can exercise that intelligence and explore their environment and diversity.
Before they give birth, sows use straw or leaves and twigs to build a comfortable and safe nest in which to nurse their litter.
But in today's factory farms, pregnant sows are kept in crates so narrow that they can not turn around, or even make more than a step forward or backward.
They lie on bare concrete without straw or any other form of bedding.
The piglets are taken from the sow as soon as possible for her to get pregnant again, but they never leave the shed before being led to the slaughter.
Defenders of these production methods argue that this is a regrettable but necessary response to the population's demand for food continues to grow.
On the contrary, when we confine animals in factory farms, we have to grow food for them.
The animals burn most of the energy from the food just to breathe and keep their bodies warm, so we will reap in the end only a small fraction, usually no more than a third and sometimes only a tenth of the value of the food we give them.
In contrast, cows grazing in the meadows eat food that we can not digest, which means they add to the amount of food available to us.
It is tragic that countries like China and India, as they get richer, copying Western methods and parquent animals in huge industrial farms to supply more meat and eggs for their middle classes developing.
If this continues, the result will be animal suffering on a larger scale than what currently exists in the West, more damage to the environment and an increase in heart disease and cancers of the digestive system.
This will also be totally ineffective.
As consumers, we have the power and the moral obligation to refuse to support farming methods cruel to animals and bad for us.
