We learned earlier this month at the request of China's rulers, Microsoft closed the website of a Chinese blogger hosted by a Microsoft service called MSN Spaces.
The blogger, Zhao Jing, had published information about a strike by journalists at The Beijing New, who had followed the dismissal of the free editor - Journal thinker.
Microsoft's action raises a question - key: Internet can - it really be a liberating force that authoritarian governments can not control as easily as newspapers, radio and television?
How ironic, when you think that the founder and CEO of Microsoft, Bill Gates, has been an enthusiastic advocate of this view.
Last October, he just said, "There really is no way, in a broad sense, repress information today, and I think it's a wonderful progress that should all rejoice ... C ' is a means of communication with an opening and a total freedom, and that's what makes it so unique. "
Despite these sentiments, Microsoft is helping its best the Chinese authorities to censor information.
A door - Microsoft spokesman said that the company had blocked "many sites" in China, and is known for several months that the tool used to make Chinese blogs filters words like "democracy" and "human man "when they appear in the blog titles.
Microsoft's defense is that it must "comply with local and global laws."
But the MSN Spaces sites are maintained on servers States - united.
Local laws to be observed in this case are those of the States - United and discussions Zhao Jing on the Beijing journalists' strike does not violate any of them.
There is no global laws that prevent Chinese people from discussing events that their government would prefer not to see them addressed.
The New York Times, for example, is free to publish its report on the strike, even if it is broadcast on a website that all users benefit from free access can view.
If the Chinese government does not want its citizens to read a foreign newspaper, it is for him to find a way to block access to them.
The newspaper is under no obligation to do so in his place.
Microsoft's defense is so long.
We can only guess the real reasons that led him to close the site; and fear of repercussions against its commercial interests in China may well be a major factor.
Of course, a company can and should place limits on the use of its services.
The absolutist line, which is to leave absolute freedom prevail, crumbles in the face of uncomfortable examples.
According to Gates, Microsoft might prevent the use of its services if they were used to disseminate instructions for making a nuclear bomb, sending of Nazi propaganda in Germany, where it is illegal, and to propagate the pedophile pornography.
These examples are - they really valid?
In his classic defense of freedom of expression, On Liberty, John Stuart Mill argued that the most important reason for freedom of expression is to promote competition between the widest possible ideas and debate without hindrance is the best way to test them.
Protecting the ideas of criticism, the government turns them into rigid dogma and lifeless, they are true or not.
If we agree with Mill, then only one of Gates's examples falls into the category of expression that should be protected.
Recipes for making nuclear bombs are techniques, not ideas.
The pedophile pornography is not the expression of ideas.
We may therefore restrict both without contradicting the thesis of Mill.
(On the other hand, an essay arguing that there is nothing wrong with adults taking a sexual interest in children, and that such conduct should be permitted, expresses ideas, and also that ignoble 'they may seem to us, as such should not be censored.).
The most difficult of the three examples is that of pro Gates statements - a site for Nazi Germany.
It is easy to understand why Germany would wish to prohibit such statements.
The laws of many countries prohibit incitement to racial hatred, which can be justified, in agreement with the defense of freedom of Mill, if such legislation is closely focused on the incitement of hatred rather than on suppressing theses are as bad - they, that appeal to people's intellectual capacities.
A defender of suppression of Nazi ideas might argue that have already been tried and have failed, in the most horrendous manner imaginable, to produce a better society.
Anyway, the best possible sign that would show that Germany has overcome its Nazi past would be to focus its laws specifically on racial hatred, rather than on Nazism as such.
In any case, China's repressive measures against direct reports and discussion of events taking place in this country do not return to the suppression of a discredited political ideology, but that of a open and informed political debate.
If Bill Gates really believes that the Internet should act as a liberating force, he should ensure that Microsoft is not doing the dirty work of the Chinese government.
