Rescue of Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans agree.
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 30s.
The new version of the plan of 700 billion US dollars to curb the financial crisis gripping Wall Street for months has yet to be ratified by both houses of Congress.
It provides for: better control by elected its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as control over the salaries paid to executives of companies rescued.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, president of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative to the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at term a marathon two-day negotiations.
"We have made great progress toward an agreement that will be effective on the market," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything was done so as to shelter the real economy and ordinary Americans of the current crisis on Wall Street," said the Democrat.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to sprint in the final hours for fear of the effect another failure would cause on the mood of investors.
The deadline we had given was the opening of markets this morning.
Associated late to the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election were rather favorable to the agreement, however without missing to express their dissatisfaction that one is compelled to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was awarded the addition of certain provisions in the agreement, including that to allow homeowners to keep their homes and that the wages of leaders of enterprises rescued by the state.
"When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary, "he commented on the airwaves of American television.
Asked another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, responded: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The outline that I read [show] that this is something we will all have to digest and with which we can move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable, "he said.
The plan seeks $ 700 billion to buy with the money of taxpayers bad debts, assets at risk and unsellable US financial institutions.
It happens after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages (subprime) before spreading to other more common forms of credit securities (ABCP) and lead to a liquidity freeze and the stampede of banks and financial institutions.
This is a group of elected Republicans who had derailed the first draft agreement last week.
Is believed to be out of this impasse since the Democrats have agreed that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
To round off the corners for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could set up new taxes to help recover his bet.
The new plan provides for payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which may be added another 100 billion if the President deems necessary.
The payment of an additional 350 billion expected to be endorsed by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that earned him dividends in case of profit and he can sell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the ability to delay foreclosures procedures regarding housing attached to home loans affected by the plan and to set limits to compensation and severance payments to executives of companies affected.
The architects of the plan would see voted on by the House of Representatives today, and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their best efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Voices have indeed continued to rise yesterday against it in both the Democrat Republican camp.
"Obviously, Washington does not hear you," said to the address of his constituents the Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the Committee on the House Finance.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not one that is to take advantage of taxpayers. "
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of the skeptics," Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but reaches the same conclusion.
"Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize, wrote in to say: we ask the Congress not to hurry and to examine carefully the way forward," he said yesterday.
Meanwhile, in Europe, there was a further proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands - the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas has indicated that it would not acquire its rival in full sinking since she lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of subprime States - States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"It is not money lost, said yesterday the Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos.
In exchange, we get voting rights in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that investors and households appreciate now that uncertain times ahead. "
Meanwhile, the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed on track to nationalize another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would resume its consideration of all outstanding loans in the bank Bradford and Bringley, more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) home loans.
