The intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee.
Which method is best suited to develop to avoid an obstacle technologies, if not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector already in nature?
For example, that of bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees have given the strategic idea starting engineers at Nissan, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini car robot, an auto control system - robotic bio - inspired type BR23C, it has equipped bees qualities, the ultimate objective of encouraging the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During his flight, each bee is its own space, oval, which actually closely resembles our secure shell protection - explained at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, director of research and development department and relationships public technology brand.
The bee's eye facets plays a crucial role, since it is able to see in all directions in a 300 degree angle.
To mimic the functions of the eye facets, engineers have addressed the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãthe laser rangefinder.
The one - it identifies obstacles in a 180 degree angle and a distance of 2 meters before the BR23C, it evaluates the distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor board, which transforms it into evasive action right away.
The perception of the barrier occurs in a fraction of a second. Then the mini car robot, mimicking the movements of a bee, immediately change direction by turning its wheels at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
